    Final report
Authors: Kelly Wolf, Miroslav Sirota, Marie Juanchich,
Claim summary 
This study aimed to replicate the main claim reported in Yang et al.’s (2013) Experiment 1. The authors reported that the more prospect’s frame was associated with risk, less were buyers willing to pay for that prospect: Framing a risky prospect as a “lottery ticket” (i.e., increased risk and uncertainty) reduced participants’ willingness to pay for the prospect, compared with to an uncertain “gift certificate” (i.e. reduced risk and uncertainty). 

Replication criteria 
The hypothesis for this study is identical to that of the original study. We hypothesize that participants in the lottery condition will have a lower mean willingness to pay than participants in the gift card condition. Participants’ willingness to pay is characterized as the minimum amount in US dollars provided by participants. No additional hypotheses are included in this experiment.
Replication result 
We collected the initial sample size of 162 in the first round of data collection. However, this did not fulfil the required analytical sample size after data exclusion. We continued collecting data until we reached the required sample size. In total, 281 participants completed the questionnaire out of which we managed to code 277 participants’ responses (4 values were excluded because it could not be coded). Finally, only the participants demonstrating a good understanding of the scenario (i.e., correctly identified that the minimal outcome is $10 lottery/gift certificate) were retained in the analytical sample. This process resulted in 168 valid responses, which fulfilled our minimal analytical sample requirement of having at least 162 participants. 

Following strictly our pre-registration protocol, we conducted an independent sample t-test on the sample of 168 participants. The participants in the lottery condition were willing to pay less (M = 17.3, SD = 16.4, Mdn = 18, n = 82) than those in the gift condition (M = 186.2, SD = 1059.2, Mdn = 10, n = 86), but the difference was not statistically significant, t(85.04) = -1.48, p =.143, Cohen’s d =-0.22. However, several values in both conditions, but especially in the gift condition, were driven by unrealistic extreme values (e.g., $ 7,000). We believe that these values indicate either a negligent response or a fundamental misunderstanding of the instructions. For this reason, we decided to diverge from our pre-registration protocol and exclude also the values higher than $20. This resulted in an analytical sample size of 147 participants. We then conducted a second independent sample t-test on the sample of 147 participants. Descriptively, the participants were willing to pay more in the lottery condition (M = 12.7, SD = 7.2, Mdn = 14, n = 71) than in the gift condition (M = 11.0, SD = 6.3, Mdn = 10, n = 76), even though the difference was not statistically significant, t(139.44) = 1.53, p =.129, Cohen’s d = 0.26. This does not confirm the hypothesis that framing a risky prospect as a “lottery ticket” reduces participants’ willingness to pay for the prospect, compared with to an uncertain “gift certificate”. 

Deviations from preregistration
We used an additional independent sample t-test to analyse the data, after removing unrealistic extreme values (i.e., > $20). This resulted in a sample size of 147 participants. The additional test is identical to the planned test, both are independent sample t-tests with the same variables.

Description of materials provided
All materials relating to this project, including ethical approval, survey items, power analysis, script and data are publicly available on Open Science Framework, at https://osf.io/r924g/. 

References

Yang, Y., Vosgerau, J., & Loewenstein, G. (2013). Framing Influences Willingness to Pay	but Not Willingness to Accept. Journal of Marketing Research, 50(6), 725–738. 	https://doi.org/10.1509/jmr.12.0430

